# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: airbox
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:airbox/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:airbox/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:airbox/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:airbox/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:airbox/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:airbox/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:airbox/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:airbox/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:airbox/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:airbox/air-filter] However, as long as a pleated-paper filter is sized appropriately for the airflow volumes encountered in a particular application, such filters present only a trivial restriction to flow and pressure drop until the filter has become significantly clogged with dirt.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:airbox/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.
[src:airbox/air-filter] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:airbox/air-filter] In an extremely modified engine lacking the space for a cone-based air filter, some will opt to install a simple stainless steel mesh over the hot turbo to reduce certain particles sizes from entering the engine via the turbo.
[src:airbox/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:airbox/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:airbox/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:airbox/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:airbox/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:airbox/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:airbox/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:airbox/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:airbox/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:airbox/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:airbox/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:airbox/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:airbox/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:airbox/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:airbox/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:airbox/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:airbox/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:airbox/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:airbox/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:airbox/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:airbox/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:airbox/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:airbox/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] The **Alfa Romeo Montreal** is a sports car produced by the Italian automobile manufacturer Alfa Romeo from 1970 to 1977.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] The Alfa Romeo Montreal was introduced as a concept car in 1967 at the Expo 67, held in Montreal, Quebec, Canada.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Originally, the concept cars were displayed without any model name, but the public took to calling it *The Montreal*.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] It was a 2-door 2+2 coupe designed by Marcello Gandini at Bertone using the 1.6-litre engine of the Giulia TI and the short wheelbase chassis of the Giulia Sprint GT.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Paolo Martin is credited for the prototype's instrument cluster.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] One of the two concept cars built for Expo 67 is displayed in the Alfa Romeo Historical Museum in Arese, Italy, while the other is in the museum storage.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] This engine was inspired by, but not derived from the 2-litre V8 used in the 33 Stradale and in the Tipo 33 sports prototype racer, and shares no parts with those engines.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] The chassis and running gear of the production car were shared with the Giulia GTV coupé and comprised double wishbone suspension with coil springs and dampers at the front and a live axle with limited slip differential at the rear.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Since the concept car was already unofficially known as *The Montreal*, Alfa Romeo kept this name for the production car as well.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Despite the name, Alfa Romeo chose not to submit the Montreal to emissions testing in the United States or Canada, and ultimately the car was never officially exported to those markets.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Stylistically, the most eye-catching feature is the car's front end with four headlamps partly covered by unusual "grilles", that retract when the lamps are switched on (a compromise Gandini had to make to meet regulations for the height of headlamps in certain markets).
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Another stylistic element is the NACA duct on the bonnet.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] The duct is actually blocked off since its purpose is not to draw air into the engine, but to optically hide the power bulge.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] The slats behind the doors contain the cabin vents, but apart from that only serve cosmetic purposes.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] The Montreal was more expensive to buy than the Jaguar E-Type or the Porsche 911.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] When launched in the UK it was priced at £5,077, rising to £5,549 in August 1972 and to £6,999 by mid-1976.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] This dampened the interest of the buying public which was already considering fuel efficient options due to the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Production of the Montreal came to an end in 1977 after 3,917 examples had been built.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Production was split between the Alfa Romeo plant in Arese and Carrozzeria Bertone's plants in Caselle and Grugliasco outside Turin.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Alfa Romeo produced the chassis and engine and mechanicals and sent the chassis to Caselle where Bertone fitted the body.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] After body fitment, the car was sent to Grugliasco to be degreased, partly zinc coated, manually spray painted and have the interior fitted.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Finally, the car was returned to Arese to have the engine and mechanicals installed.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Because of this production method, there is not necessarily any correspondence between chassis number, engine number and production date.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] The Montreal remained generally unchanged until it was finally removed from pricelists in 1977.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] By then, production had long ceased as Alfa struggled to sell its remaining stock.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] A Group 4 Montreal was built by Autodelta in late 1972.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] It was launched at the London Racing Car Show in January 1973.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] It was sold to Alfa Romeo Germany to be used in the DRM series for GT cars.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Ready to race in May 1973, the car was entrusted to specialist racing team of Dieter Gleich, who was also the principle driver.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] The Autodelta race car had a 2,997 cc engine with maximum power output of 370 hp (276 kW) at 9,000 rpm.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] Without any further development the car was outdated very soon.
[src:airbox/alfa-romeo-montreal] A Montreal was also campaigned in the United States but also without success.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] BMW made 1,000 S1000RRs in 2009 to satisfy World Superbike homologation requirements, but expanded production for commercial sale of the bike in 2010.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] It has a standard anti-lock braking system, with an optional electronic traction control.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] With 133.6 kW (179.2 hp; 181.6 PS) to the rear wheel, it was the most powerful motorcycle in the class on the dyno.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] BMW S1000RR is currently the second fastest road legal bike, surpassing the Kawasaki Ninja H2 in most scenarios.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] It goes up to 310kmph in the latest generation and accelerates to 300kmph in just 20 seconds.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The S1000RR was released in 2009 and was considered the best-equipped sport bike in the *1000 cc* category, and with a bore and stroke of 80.0 mm × 49.7 mm (3.1 in × 2.0 in), it also had the biggest bore in its class.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The bike came factory fitted with ABS and dynamic traction control, a first for road-going superbike at the time.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] On top of this, it came standard with three riding modes (Wet, Sport and Race) with an additional riding mode (Slick) available only after connecting a dongle, that you received with the bike, to a special jack under the seat.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] It was also the first production motorcycle to offer an optional quick shifter.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] This is a clutchless shifter that allowed you to upshift with no clutch actuation even at full throttle.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] After the initial delivery of motorcycles the factory started shipping them with a software governor that limited RPM to 9000 for a short break in period that was later removed by the dealers.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The 2011 bike remained unchanged, keeping the same livery options, engine, chassis and suspension.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] In 2012, the bike received slightly more significant changes.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] It was given new throttle maps for each of the four riding modes, to combat throttle response issues that customers were facing with the bike.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] To further aid this issue, BMW updated the throttle tube to be lighter and have a shorter pull.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The intake and exhaust systems received updates: the ram air intake was made 20% larger and the catalytic converters were moved from the headers to the muffler, which allowed the oil sump heat shield to be removed, saving a small amount of weight.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The optional DTC (Dynamic Traction Control) was updated, smoothing the butterfly valve action when a wheelie was detected, providing a less violent response to the bike's front wheel lifting off the ground.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The chassis was updated; the front suspension was lifted by 4 mm (0.2 in) and the rear was lowered by 5 mm (0.2 in).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The wheelbase was reduced by nearly 10 mm (0.4 in) through a tooth addition in the rear sprocket (45).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The angle of the steering head was revised and the offset of the fork was reduced by 2.5 mm (0.1 in).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The triple clamp on top of the fork was uprated to forged aluminium.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Lastly, the spring rates and valving in the suspension were revised, including special check valves to allow for completely independent compression and rebound adjustment, coupled with a 10-way adjustable steering damper.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The 2012 visual updates included a new face of the tachometer as well as new heel plates, a slimmer-looking tail section and reshaped side panels with plastic winglets: these were said to improve aerodynamics at speed.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Smaller visual updates included grilles on the side of the tank plastics and a new "RR" logo.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] In 2013 the bike did not receive updates to the same extent as the 2012 bike.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] However, BMW introduced the HP4 variant, a more track-oriented version of the standard S1000RR.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The 2013 HP4 saw the ride-by-wire system again taken to a level unseen outside of the WSBK and MotoGP.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The HP4 was fitted with a Dynamic Dampening Control (DDC) system that updates and makes changes to the suspension every 11 milliseconds, responding to various sensors as well as throttle input and is adjustable on the fly, a first on any production motorcycle.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The bike was given an electronic controlled interference pipe and acoustic valves, allowing air to flow into the exhaust and burn unused fuel as well as upgraded Brembo Monobloc brake calipers.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The riding modes of the HP4 differ from the standard bike, in that it allows for all 144 kW (193 hp; 196 PS) to be accessed in four modes.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The HP4 also introduced combined braking, meaning that in all modes except slick, the back brake is applied automatically when the rider applies the front brake.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] It was offered in multiple race kit packages, ranging from the stock claimed 144 kW (193 hp; 196 PS) of the S1000RR all the way up to a claimed 158 kW (212 hp; 215 PS).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The 2013 HP4 was also equipped with more electronic features, launch control and pit-mode, all accessible from the controls on the handlebars.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The bike was also given its own colorway and an HP4-specific tachometer face.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The 2014 S1000RR saw some more minor updates and the first race-ABS as standard.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The handlebars were also slightly modified, as well as some very minor changes to the fairings.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] In 2015, the S1000RR saw major updates and changes.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Notably, the bike now weighed 4 kg (8.8 lb) less and gained 4.4 kW (5.9 hp; 6.0 PS) to a claimed output of 148 kW (198 hp; 201 PS).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] This was achieved through reshaping the ports, a new cam profile, lighter valves and shorter velocity stacks drawing from a larger airbox.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] An all-new exhaust has also been implemented, drawing from the previous years HP4, adding a controlled interference pipe and acoustic valves.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] More options made available in the 2015 variant were included in the "Dynamic Package" which included BMW's Quickshift Assist Pro, allowing for clutchless up and downshifts.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] BMW also introduced a "Race Package" which gave the user DDC from the HP4, a "Pro" riding mode as well as launch control, a customizable pit limiter and cruise control.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] To the electronics, BMW again added smoother front wheel lift intervention and a new "User" mode, where the rider is able to customize some defined parameters, allowing for a fully personalized riding experience.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] More learnings from the HP4 include combined braking (automatically activating the rear brake when the front brake is applied), on-the-fly ABS and DTC control and lean angle sensors that provide a readout on the dash.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The 2015 bikes lighter chassis consists of four individual aluminium cast pieces welded together with the engine tilted forward at a 32-degree angle and integrated as a load-bearing element.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The fork overlap of the immersion tubes was reduced to 6 mm (0.2 in) and the steering head angle increased 0.5 degrees to 66.5 without any change in the yoke offset.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The swingarm pivot point was lowered by 3 mm (0.1 in) and the wheelbase lengthened by 15 mm (0.6 in).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The new chassis geometry provides increased rider feedback from the front end the rear wheel.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The visual updates to the S1000RR were also vast, with the asymmetric headlights being swapped (high beam left, low beam right), a softer nose and all new colorways.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The muffler was changed to a larger can, while the fairings became more aerodynamically advanced adding vents and slips to allow for better stability at high speed.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] In 2017, a non-street legal, track-only variant, the BMW HP4 Race was added, made in a limited production run of 750 units.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The S1000RR received a full model change for 2019 at the November 2018 EICMA, Milan, Italy.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The 999 cc (61.0 cu in) four-cylinder engine is entirely new, which is claimed to produce 152 kW (204 hp; 207 PS) at 13,500 rpm (up 4.5 kW (6.0 hp; 6.1 PS) from the previous iteration) and 113 N⋅m (83 lbf⋅ft) of torque at 11,000 rpm.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] This new engine employs BMW *ShiftCam* technology on the intake side, which varies intake valve timing and lift.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The system has sliding concentric outer shafts, with two different cam profiles on them, on a splined inner shaft with the drive on one end.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] An ECU-controlled motor switches between low- and high-speed cams at 9,000 rpm in under 10 milliseconds, which produce soft, low-lift, short-duration cams for low-down and midrange torque, then a more aggressive profile cams for peak power production.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The outer shafts are moved by a movable pin engaging in a cammed slot on the shaft, which slides the outer camshaft section left and right as needed.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] BMW claims the addition of this system gives the S1000RR a more linear torque curve than its predecessor.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Aside from power increase, the S1000RR's engine gains a weight loss of nearly 4 kg (9 lb) and a more compact external design.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] This was achieved through the use of specialized parts, like hollow-bored titanium intake valves and new DLC rocker arms that are said to be 25% lighter.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The camshafts are now directly powered by the crankshaft, thus eliminating the need for the previous idler gear.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The water and oil pumps are combined into one component for a compact design.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The exhaust system is also 1.28 kg (2.8 lb) lighter on the 2019 model, which contributes to a total 11 kg (24 lb) loss in comparison to its predecessor.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] This brings the overall curb weight of 197 kg (434 lb).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] There are four preset riding modes: "Rain", "Road", "Dynamic" and "Race", as well as three "Pro" modes, which can be custom tuned and come with a three-stage engine-braking adjustment.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The chassis has been revamped for the 2019 S1000RR, which is focusing on weight reduction while improving handling.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The aluminium perimeter frame drops 1.28 kg (2.8 lb) of weight, now using the engine as more of a load-bearing unit and reducing width by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] With a focus on improving agility, BMW steepened the steering head angle to 66.9 degrees and reduced trail to 93.9 mm (3.70 in).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The wheelbase has been increased by 9 mm (0.35 in).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The front suspension is a 45 mm (1.77 in) inverted telescopic fork, which is decreased in size from 46 mm (1.81 in), that is claimed to optimize flex and midcorner feel.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] BMW Dynamic Damping Control (DDC) semi-active suspension is still available on the S1000RR as an option, which has been enhanced with updated damping settings.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The fuel tank and seat design are now slimmer.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The front fairing is narrower and more aerodynamic than its predecessor, also housing twin symmetrical LED headlights, with the intake directly centered at the front for optimum airflow.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The instrumentation now uses a 6.5-inch TFT display, which has four preset settings.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The M package, the first of any BMW motorcycle, is available, which includes motorsport paint finish, M carbon fiber wheels, an M lightweight battery, M Chassis Kit with rear ride height adjustment and swingarm pivot, the M Sport seat and a "Pro" riding mode.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The package reduces the weight further to 193.5 kg (427 lb).
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The higher-spec variant of the S1000RR, called **M1000RR**, was unveiled in September 2020 intended as a basis for racing but still road legal.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The first BMW motorcycle to carry the 'M' prefix normally associated with cars, the machine has extensive modifications in powerplant, chassis, exhaust and braking.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The fairing has aerodynamic winglets that provide downforce.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Three variants of the S1000 RR announced on 30 September 2022 are the M package, Style Passion and Black Storm Metallic.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The factory race bike used in the Superbike World Championship differs in a number of ways from the production bike.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Its engine has a higher compression ratio of 14.0:1 compared with 13.0:1, and it delivers over 150 kW (201 hp; 204 PS) at 14,000 rpm, compared with 144 kW (193 hp; 196 PS) at 13,000 rpm.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The race bike has a 44 mm (1.73 in) Öhlins forks, compared with a 46 mm (1.81 in) ZF Sachs forks.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Until 2012, it had a 16.5-inch front wheel and a 16-inch rear wheel instead of a 17-inch (for 2013 World Superbike season, 17-inch rims became mandatory) and an MRA racing 'double-bubble' windshield.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Most significantly, it has a wet weight of 162 kg (357 lb) compared with 207.7 kg (458 lb) for the production model.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] On 26 June 2008, Spanish rider Rubén Xaus signed to ride the bike for the factory BMW Motorrad team.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] On 25 September 2008, Australian former double Superbike World Champion Troy Corser signed to complete the team's two-rider lineup for 2009.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] In the 2009 Superbike World Championship season, the highest race result achieved by Corser was fifth place in the Czech Republic, and Xaus achieved seventh place in Italy.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] During the 2010 FIM Superstock 1000 Championship season, Ayrton Badovini dominated by winning every single race but one on the S1000RR.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] This result was significant because the Superstock class of WSBK is where the machines most closely resemble the stock offerings at the showroom.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] On 13 May 2012, Italian rider Marco Melandri riding for the factory BMW Motorrad team was the first to secure a win for the S1000RR in World Superbike competition at the British round in Donington Park.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] His teammate Leon Haslam came in second giving BMW a "One Two" finish.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] On 2012 Qatar Grand Prix, US rider Colin Edwards rode a S1000RR engined motorcycle for the Forward Racing team.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] This history making inaugural CRT Class debut, where 1,000 cc tuned factory production motorcycle engines competed for the first time alongside the current MotoGP machines.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The S1000RR engined Suter machine placed first in its class and finished 12th overall.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The S1000RR has been used by various riders at the Isle of Man TT since 2010.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] On 31 May 2014, Michael Dunlop won the superbike class race on his factory-prepared bike entered by Hawk Racing, a UK-based BSB team operating as *Buildbase BMW Motorrad*, breaking a 75-year gap between wins for BMW.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Three days later, Dunlop repeated his victory in the *Superstock* class, running under his own *MD Racing BMW* banner.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] He stated "...this is a great result for BMW.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] It’s great for a manufacturer when a road bike wins a TT”.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Dunlop completed a hat-trick of BMW victories with a Senior TT win on Friday, 6 June.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Peter Hickman won the Macau Grand Prix in 2015 and 2016.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] In March 2010, BMW released a video on YouTube titled "The oldest trick in the world", which highlighted the S1000RR's acceleration by pulling a tablecloth off a long 20-seat dining table without disturbing the place settings and table decorations.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] Its popularity turned the ad viral, with 1.4 million views in the first ten days, and more than 3.7 million views as of October 2010.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The October 27, 2010 *MythBusters* episode "Tablecloth Chaos" tested whether the trick could be reproduced.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The stunt was replicated in detail, with the exception that a different and less powerful motorcycle was used—a Buell 1125R, owned and ridden by the show's co-presenter Jamie Hyneman.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] The opinion of the television program was that the video was fake as the only way it could be reproduced was by placing a plastic sheet on top of the tablecloth—thus eliminating any contact between the tablecloth and the table settings.
[src:airbox/bmw-s1000rr] BMW issued a recall for bikes built between 1 September 2011, through 10 April 2012 to address an issue with bolts that secure the connecting rods to the crankshaft that could loosen at high engine speeds.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A **carburetor** (also spelled **carburettor** or **carburetter**) is a device used by a gasoline internal combustion engine to control and mix air and fuel entering the engine.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The primary method of adding fuel to the intake air is through the Venturi effect or Bernoulli's principle or with a pitot tube in the main metering circuit, though various other components are also used to provide extra fuel or air in specific circumstances.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Since the 1990s, carburetors have been largely replaced by fuel injection for cars and trucks, but carburetors are still used by some small engines (e.g. lawnmowers, generators, and concrete mixers) and motorcycles.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In addition, they are still widely used on piston-engine–driven aircraft.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Diesel engines have always used fuel injection instead of carburetors, as they do not compress an air-fuel mix and instead require fuel injection much later in the compression stroke.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The term "carburetor" is derived from the English verb *carburet*, meaning "to charge with hydrocarbons"; in early motoring books the product of the carburetor is *carburetted air*, i.e. air charged with hydrocarbon vapour.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This meaning superseded that from the late eighteenth century in which *carburet* was a noun for which we now use the word *carbide*.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A carburetor charges the intake air with vapour from a hydrocarbon-based fuel, such as petrol or autogas.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The name is spelled "carburetor" in American English and "carburettor" in British English.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Colloquial abbreviations include "carb" in the UK and North America or "carby" in Australia.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Air from the atmosphere enters the carburetor (usually via an air cleaner), has fuel added within the carburetor, then the air fuel mixture leaves the carburetor and enters the inlet manifold, then through the inlet valve(s), and finally into the combustion chamber.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Most engines use a single carburetor shared among all of the cylinders, though some high-performance engines historically had multiple carburetors and/or throats.
[src:airbox/carburetor] If the tube is a constant diameter the configuration is slightly simpler than in the cross-section diagram shown above right.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In most cases (except for the *accelerator pump*), the driver pressing the throttle pedal does not directly increase the fuel entering the engine.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Instead, the airflow through the carburetor increases, which in turn increases the amount of fuel drawn into the intake mixture.
[src:airbox/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a reduction of area along the air flow rather than from ambient pressure to the fuel entry point the effect can be described as the Venturi effect, but that is still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:airbox/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a dynamic pressure (facing the incoming air) within the air entry point rather than from ambient pressure instead the carbureter can be described as the Pitot tube type, but that is also still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The actual fuel and air flows are more complicated and need correction.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This might be done variously at lower speeds or higher speeds, or over the whole range by a variable emulsion device to add air to the fuel after the main jets/s.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Zenith-Stromberg) variable jet carburetors, it was mainly controlled by varying the jet size.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The orientation of the carburetor is a key design consideration.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Older engines used **updraft** carburetors, where the air enters from below the carburetor and exits through the top.
[src:airbox/carburetor] From the late 1930s, **downdraft** carburetors become more commonly used (especially in the United States), along with **side draft** carburetors (especially in Europe).
[src:airbox/carburetor] The main metering circuit usually consists of barrel/s which reduces to a narrow part where the air is at its highest speed, forming a choke or venturi.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Fuel is usually introduced into the air stream at that narrow part through small tubes leading from the main jet.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The change in area is only necessary for a Venturi carburetor but in other configurations the barrel/s can be of constant area with the fuel entry anywhere along it.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Downstream of a choke or venturi is a throttle (usually in the form of a butterfly valve) which is used to control the amount of air entering the carburetor.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In a car, this throttle is usually mechanically connected to the vehicle's throttle pedal, which varies engine speed.
[src:airbox/carburetor] At lesser throttle openings, the air speed may be insufficient to maintain the main fuel flow, so then the fuel may be supplied by the carburetor's idle and off-idle circuits usually near the narrow gap between the edge of the butterfly plate and the body to give sufficient local air speed.
[src:airbox/carburetor] At greater throttle openings, the speed of air increases, which lowers the pressure of the air and draws more fuel into the airstream.
[src:airbox/carburetor] At the same time, the reduced manifold vacuum results in less fuel flow through the idle and off-idle circuits.
[src:airbox/carburetor] During cold weather fuel vaporizes less readily and tends to condense on the walls of the intake manifold, starving the cylinders of fuel and making cold starts difficult.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Additional fuel is required (for a given amount of air) to start and run the engine until it warms up, provided by a *choke valve*.
[src:airbox/carburetor] While the engine is warming up the choke valve is partially closed, restricting the flow of air at the entrance to the carburetor.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This increases the vacuum in the main metering circuit, causing more fuel to be supplied to the engine via the main jets.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Prior to the late 1950s the choke was manually operated by the driver, often using a lever or knob on the dashboard.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Since then, automatic chokes became more commonplace.
[src:airbox/carburetor] These either use a bimetallic thermostat to automatically regulate the choke based on the temperature of the engine's coolant liquid, an electrical resistance heater to do so, or air drawn through a tube connected to an engine exhaust source.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A choke left closed after the engine has warmed up increases the engine's fuel consumption and exhaust gas emissions, and causes the engine to run rough and lack power due to an over-rich fuel mixture.
[src:airbox/carburetor] However, excessive fuel can flood an engine and prevent it from starting.
[src:airbox/carburetor] To remove the excess fuel, many carburetors with automatic chokes allow it to be held open (by manually, depressing the accelerator pedal to the floor and briefly holding it there while cranking the starter) to allow extra air into the engine until the excess fuel is cleared out.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Another method used by carburetors to improve the operation of a cold engine is a *fast idle cam*, which is connected to the choke and prevents the throttle from closing fully while the choke is in operation.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The resulting increase in idle speed provides a more stable idle for a cold engine (by better atomizing the cold fuel) and helps the engine warm up quicker.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The system within a carburetor that meters fuel when the engine is running at low RPM.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The idle circuit is generally activated by vacuum near the (near closed) throttle plate, where the air speed increases to cause a low-pressure area in the idle passage/port, thus causing fuel to flow through the idle jet.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The idle jet is set at some constant value by the carburetor manufacturer, thus flowing a specified amount of fuel.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Many carburetors use an off-idle circuit, which includes an additional fuel jet which is briefly used as the throttle starts to open.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This jet is located in a low-pressure area caused by the high air speed near the (partly closed) throttle.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The additional fuel it provides is used to compensate for the reduced vacuum that occurs when the throttle is opened, thus smoothing the transition from the idle circuit to the main metering circuit.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In a four-stroke engine it is often desirable to provide extra fuel to the engine at high loads (to increase the power output and reduce engine knocking).
[src:airbox/carburetor] A 'power valve', which is a spring-loaded valve in the carburetor that is held shut by engine vacuum, is often used to do so.
[src:airbox/carburetor] As the airflow through the carburetor increases, the reduced manifold vacuum pulls the power valve open, allowing more fuel into the main metering circuit.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In a two-stroke engine, the carburetor power valve operates in the opposite manner: in most circumstances the valve allows extra fuel into the engine, then at a certain engine RPM it closes to reduce the fuel entering the engine.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This is done in order to extend the engine's maximum RPM, since many two-stroke engines can temporarily achieve higher RPM with a leaner air-fuel ratio.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This is not to be confused with the unrelated exhaust power valve arrangements used on two-stroke engines.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A metering rod or step-up rod system is sometimes used as an alternative to a power valve in a four-stroke engine in order to supply extra fuel at high loads.
[src:airbox/carburetor] One end of the rods is tapered, which sits in the main metering jets and acts as a valve for fuel flow in the jets.
[src:airbox/carburetor] At high engine loads, the rods are lifted away from the jets (either mechanically or using manifold vacuum), increasing the volume of fuel flow through the jet.
[src:airbox/carburetor] These systems have been used by the Rochester Quadrajet and in the 1950s Carter carburetors.
[src:airbox/carburetor] While the main metering circuit can adequately supply fuel to the engine in steady-state conditions, the inertia of fuel (being higher than that of air) causes a temporary shortfall as the throttle is opened.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Therefore, an accelerator pump is often used to briefly provide extra fuel as the throttle is opened.
[src:airbox/carburetor] When the driver presses the throttle pedal, a small piston or diaphragm pump injects extra fuel directly into the carburetor throat.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The accelerator pump can also be used to "prime" an engine with extra fuel prior to attempting a cold start.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In order to ensure an adequate supply at all times, carburetors include a reservoir of fuel, called a "float chamber" or "float bowl".
[src:airbox/carburetor] Fuel is delivered to the float chamber by a fuel pump or by gravity with the fuel tank located higher than the carburetor.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A floating inlet valve regulates the fuel entering the float chamber, assuring a constant level.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In some small engines that may instead of a float chamber just use a fuel tank close below the carburetor and use the fuel suction to supply the fuel.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Unlike in a fuel injected engine, the fuel system in a carbureted engine is not pressurized.
[src:airbox/carburetor] For engines where the intake air travelling through the carburetor is pressurized (such as where the carburetor is downstream of a supercharger) the entire carburetor must be contained in an airtight pressurized box to operate.
[src:airbox/carburetor] However, this is not necessary where the carburetor is upstream of the supercharger.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Problems of fuel boiling and vapor lock can occur in carbureted engines, especially in hotter climates.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Since the float chamber is located close to the engine, heat from the engine (including for several hours after the engine is shut off) can cause the fuel to heat up to the point of vaporization.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This causes air bubbles in the fuel (similar to the air bubbles that necessitate brake bleeding), which prevents the flow of fuel and is known as 'vapor lock'.
[src:airbox/carburetor] If an engine must be operated when the carburetor is not in an upright orientation (for example in a chainsaw or airplane), a float chamber and gravity activated float valve would not be suitable.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Instead, a diaphragm chamber is typically used.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This consists of a flexible diaphragm on one side of the fuel chamber, connected to a needle valve which regulates the fuel entering the chamber.
[src:airbox/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber (controlled by the throttling valve/butterfly valve) decreases, the diaphragm moves inward (downward), which closes the needle valve to admit less fuel.
[src:airbox/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber increases, the diaphragm moves outward (upward) which opens the needle valve to admit more fuel, allowing the engine to generate more power.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A balanced state is reached which creates a steady fuel reservoir level, that remains constant in any orientation.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The basic design for a carburetor consists of a single venturi (main metering circuit), though designs with two or four venturi (two-barrel and four-barrel carburetors respectively) are also quite commonplace.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Typically the barrels consist of "primary" barrel(s) used for lower load situations and secondary barrel(s) activating when required to provide additional air/fuel at higher loads.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The primary and secondary venturi are often sized differently and incorporate different features to suit the situations in which they are used.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Many four-barrel carburetors use two primary and two secondary barrels.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A four-barrel design of two primary and two secondary barrels was commonly used in V8 engines to conserve fuel at low engine speeds while still affording an adequate supply at high.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The use of multiple carburetors (e.g., a carburetor for each cylinder or pair of cylinders) also results in the intake air being drawn through multiple venturi.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Some high-performance engines have used multiple two-barrel or four-barrel carburetors, for example six two-barrel carburetors on Ferrari V12s.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In 1826, American engineer Samuel Morey received a patent for a "gas or vapor engine", which had a carburetor that mixed turpentine and air.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In 1888/1889 German engineer Siegfried Marcus produced a car powered by a petrol engine (which also debuted the first magneto ignition system).
[src:airbox/carburetor] Karl Benz introduced his single-cylinder four-stroke powered Benz Patent-Motorwagen in 1885.
[src:airbox/carburetor] All three of these engines used surface carburetors, which operated by moving air across the top of a vessel containing the fuel.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The first float-fed carburetor design, which used an atomizer nozzle, was introduced by German engineers Wilhelm Maybach and Gottlieb Daimler in their 1885 *Grandfather Clock engine*.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The Butler Petrol Cycle car—built in England in 1888—also used a float-fed carburetor.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In 1892 Maybach produced an important carburetor with a jet spraying into a venturi, as would become the norm; this was patented in 1893.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The first carburetor for a stationary engine was patented in 1893 by Hungarian engineers János Csonka and Donát Bánki.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The first four-barrel carburetors were the Carter Carburetor WCFB and the identical Rochester 4GC, introduced in various General Motors models for 1952.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Oldsmobile referred the new carburetor as the "Quadri-Jet" (original spelling) while Buick called it the "Airpower".
[src:airbox/carburetor] In the United States, carburetors were the common method of fuel delivery for most US-made gasoline (petrol) engines until the late 1980s, when fuel injection became the preferred method.
[src:airbox/carburetor] One of the last motorsport users of carburetors was NASCAR, which switched to electronic fuel injection after the 2011 Sprint Cup series.
[src:airbox/carburetor] NASCAR still uses the four-barrel carburetor in the NASCAR Xfinity Series.
[src:airbox/carburetor] In Europe, carburetors were largely replaced by fuel injection in the late 1980s, although fuel injection had been increasingly used in luxury cars and sports cars since the 1970s.
[src:airbox/carburetor] EEC legislation required all vehicles sold and produced in member countries to have a catalytic converter after December 1992.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This legislation had been in the pipeline for some time, with many cars becoming available with catalytic converters or fuel injection from around 1990.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A significant concern for aircraft engines is the formation of ice inside the carburetor.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The temperature of air within the carburetor can be reduced by up to 40 °C (72 °F), due to a combination of the reduced air pressure in the venturi and the latent heat of the evaporating fuel.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The conditions during the descent to landing are particularly conducive to icing, since the engine is run at idle for a prolonged period with the throttle closed.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Icing can also occur in cruise conditions at altitude.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A carburetor heat system is often used to prevent icing.
[src:airbox/carburetor] This system consists of a secondary air intake which passes around the exhaust, in order to heat the air before it enters the carburetor.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Typically, the system is operated by the pilot manually switching the intake air to travel via the heated intake path as required.
[src:airbox/carburetor] The carburetor heat system reduces the power output (due to the lower density of heated air) and causes the intake air filter to be bypassed, therefore the system is only used when there is a risk of icing.
[src:airbox/carburetor] If the engine is operating at idle RPM, another method to prevent icing is to periodically open the throttle, which increases the air temperature within the carburetor.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Carburetor icing also occurs on other applications and various methods have been employed to solve this problem.
[src:airbox/carburetor] On inline engines the intake and exhaust manifolds are on the same side of the head.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Heat from the exhaust is used to warm the intake manifold and in turn the carburetor.
[src:airbox/carburetor] On V configurations, exhaust gases were directed from one head through the intake cross over to the other head.
[src:airbox/carburetor] One method for regulating the exhaust flow on the cross over for intake warming was a weighted eccentric butterfly valve called a heat riser that remained closed at idle and opened at higher exhaust flow.
[src:airbox/carburetor] Some vehicles used a heat stove around the exhaust manifold.
[src:airbox/carburetor] It was connected to the air filter intake via tubing and supplied warmed air to the air filter.
[src:airbox/carburetor] A vacuum controlled butterfly valve pre heat tube on the intake horn of the air cleaner would open allowing cooler air when engine load increased.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The concept of Helmholtz resonance is fundamental in various fields, including acoustics, engineering, and physics.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The resonator itself, termed a *Helmholtz resonator*, consists of two key components: a cavity and a neck.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The size and shape of these components are crucial in determining the resonant frequency, which is the frequency at which the system naturally oscillates.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] In the context of acoustics, Helmholtz resonance is instrumental in the design and analysis of musical instruments, architectural acoustics, and sound engineering.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] It is also utilized in automotive engineering for noise reduction and in designing exhaust systems.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The underlying principle involves the vibration of the air mass in the neck of the resonator, acting analogously to a mass on a spring.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] When external forces, such as airflow, disturb this air mass, it oscillates and causes the air within the cavity to resonate.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] This phenomenon is characterized by its sharp and high-amplitude resonance curve, making it distinct from other types of acoustic resonance.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Since its conceptualization in the 19th century, Helmholtz resonance has continued to be a subject of study and application, illustrating the interplay between simple physical systems and complex vibrational phenomena.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Helmholtz described in his 1863 book *On the Sensations of Tone* an apparatus able to pick out specific frequencies from a complex sound, which is now known as a Helmholtz resonator.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] It consists of a rigid container of a known volume, nearly spherical in shape, with a small neck and hole in one end and a larger hole in the other end to emit the sound.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] When the resonator's 'nipple' is placed inside one's ear, a specific frequency of the complex sound can be picked out and heard clearly.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] In his book Helmholtz explains: When we "apply a resonator to the ear, most of the tones produced in the surrounding air will be considerably damped; but if the proper tone of the resonator is sounded, it brays into the ear most powerfully….
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] A set of varied size resonators was sold to be used as discrete acoustic filters for the spectral analysis of complex sounds.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] There is also an adjustable type, called a universal resonator, which consists of two cylinders, one inside the other, which can slide in or out to change the volume of the cavity over a continuous range.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] An array of 10 of this type of resonator was employed in a mechanical Fourier sound analyzer designed by Rudolph Koenig.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] This resonator can also emit a variable-frequency tone when driven by a stream of air in the "tone variator" invented by William Stern, 1897.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] When air is forced into a cavity, the pressure inside increases.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] When the external force pushing the air into the cavity is removed, the higher-pressure air inside will flow out.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Due to the inertia of the moving air the cavity will be left at a pressure slightly lower than the outside, causing air to be drawn back in.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] This process repeats, with the magnitude of the pressure oscillations increasing and decreasing asymptotically after the sound starts and stops.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The port (the neck of the chamber) is placed in the ear, allowing the experimenter to hear the sound and to determine its loudness.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The resonant mass of air in the chamber is set in motion through the second hole, which is larger and doesn't have a neck.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] A gastropod seashell can form a Helmholtz resonator with low Q factor, amplifying many frequencies, resulting in the "sounds of the sea".
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The term Helmholtz resonator is now more generally applied to include bottles from which sound is generated by blowing air across the mouth of the bottle.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] In this case the length and diameter of the bottle neck also contribute to the resonance frequency and its Q factor.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] By one definition a Helmholtz resonator augments the amplitude of the vibratory motion of the enclosed air in a chamber by taking energy from sound waves passing in the surrounding air.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] In the other definition the sound waves are generated by a uniform stream of air flowing across the open top of an enclosed volume of air.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The length of the neck appears in the denominator because the inertia of the air in the neck is proportional to the length.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The volume of the cavity appears in the denominator because the spring constant of the air in the cavity is inversely proportional to its volume.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Increasing the area of the neck increases the inertia of the air proportionately, but also decreases the velocity at which the air rushes in and out.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Depending on the exact shape of the hole, the relative thickness of the sheet with respect to the size of the hole and the size of the cavity, this formula can have limitations.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] More sophisticated formulae can still be derived analytically, with similar physical explanations (although some differences matter).
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Furthermore, if the mean flow over the resonator is high (typically with a Mach number above 0.3), some corrections must be applied.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Helmholtz resonance sometimes occurs when a slightly open single car window makes a very loud sound, also called side window buffeting or wind throb.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Because cars have a large volume, the frequency of the wind throb is quite low.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Helmholtz resonance finds application in internal combustion engines, especially the airbox.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Intake systems described as 'Helmholtz Systems' have been used in the Chrysler V10 engine built for both the Dodge Viper and the Ram pickup, and several of the Buell tube-frame series of motorcycles.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The theory of Helmholtz resonators is used in motorcycle and car exhausts to alter the sound of the exhaust note and for differences in power delivery by adding chambers to the exhaust.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Exhaust resonators are also used to reduce potentially loud engine noise where the dimensions are calculated so that the waves reflected by the resonator help cancel out certain frequencies of sound in the exhaust.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] In some two-stroke engines, a Helmholtz resonator is used to remove the need for a reed valve.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] A similar effect is also used in the exhaust system of most two-stroke engines, using a reflected pressure pulse to supercharge the cylinder .
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] During the early 2010s, some Formula 1 teams used Helmholtz resonators in their cars' exhaust systems to help even out the flow of gasses that were being used to seal the edges of their diffusers as part of their exhaust blown diffuser systems.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Helmholtz resonators are also used to build acoustic liners for reducing the noise of aircraft engines, for example.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Such acoustic liners are used in most of today's aircraft engines.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The perforated sheet is usually visible from inside or outside the airplane; the honeycomb is just under it.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The thickness of the perforated sheet is of importance, as shown above.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Sometimes there are two layers of liners; they are then called "2-DOF liners" (DOF meaning degrees of freedom), as opposed to "single DOF liners".
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] This effect might also be used to reduce skin friction drag on aircraft wings by 20%.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Roman architect, described the use of bronze or pottery resonators in classical theater design.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Helmholtz resonators are used in architectural acoustics to reduce undesirable low frequency sounds (standing waves, etc.) by building a resonator tuned to the problem frequency, and putting absorbing material inside, thereby reducing it.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] An ocarina is essentially a Helmholtz resonator where the combined area of the opened finger holes determines the note played by the instrument.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The West African djembe is related to a Helmholtz resonator with a small neck area, giving it a deep bass tone, but its stretched skin, strongly coupled to the cavity makes it a more complex, and musically interesting, resonant system.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] It has been in use for thousands of years.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Conversely, the human mouth is effectively a Helmholtz resonator when it is used in conjunction with a jaw harp, shepherd's whistle, nose whistle, nose flute.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The nose blows air through an open nosepiece, into an air duct, and across an edge adjacent to the open mouth, creating the resonator.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] The volume and shape of the mouth cavity augments the pitch of the tone.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Helmholtz resonance is also used in bass-reflex speaker enclosures, with the compliance of the air mass inside the enclosure and the mass of air in the port forming a Helmholtz resonator.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] By tuning the resonant frequency of the Helmholtz resonator to the lower end of the loudspeaker's usable frequency range, the speaker's low-frequency performance is improved.
[src:airbox/helmholtz-resonance] Helmholtz resonance is one of the principles behind the way piezoelectric buzzers work: a piezoelectric disc acts as the excitation source, but it relies on the acoustic cavity resonance to produce an audible sound.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The **Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R** is a *600 cc* class motorcycle in the Ninja sport bike series from the Japanese manufacturer Kawasaki.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] It was introduced in 1995, and has been constantly updated throughout the years in response to new products from Honda, Suzuki, and Yamaha.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The ZX series is what was known as the Ninja line of Kawasaki motorcycles in the 1980s and still carries the name today.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Kawasaki introduced the ZX-6R in 1995 with very similar looks and features like the 1994 introduced ZX-9R, including the ram-air intake that had been developed by Kawasaki since the 1990 ZX-11 (ZZ-R1100).
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The first ZX-6R had a dry weight of 401.2 lb (182.0 kg), wet weight of 454 lb (206 kg), and was capable of accelerating 0 to 60 mph (0 to 97 km/h) in 3.6 seconds.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] There was a major revamp of the ZX-6R in 1998 with the Launch of the G series.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The G series saw no increase in displacement but power went from 100 BHP to 108 BHP thanks to the newly designed airbox.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The fairing was revamped, but it retained a similar design for the headlight, air intakes and windscreen.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] In 2000, the first J series replaced the G, increasing power to 112 BHP by increasing the compression ratio from 11.8:1 to 12.8:1.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The J series sported a couple of modernisations including a 180 section rear tire, second headlight, uprated generator and stick coils (coil on plug) replacing the traditional coil with HT lead.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] With strong competition from Honda's CBR600F4i, Suzuki's GSX-R600, and Yamaha's YZF-R6, Kawasaki decided on an unusual move for the late 2002 models.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] They increased the capacity of the traditional 600 cc (37 cu in) motor to 636 cubic centimetres (38.8 cu in) with the ZX-6R A1P.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] This version used the J series bodywork with the only notable differences being the "636" stickers on the fairing.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] For riders who needed bikes for displacement-restricted racing, Kawasaki also made available a limited production 599 cc (36.6 cu in) version, the Ninja ZX-6RR, but the 636 cc (38.8 cu in) ZX-6R would be their main mass production middleweight sport bike.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] In 2003, there were a number of changes to the ZX-6R, or ZX636 as it is often referred.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The engine was fuel injected and engine speed was raised around 500 RPM which resulted in a slight gain in power.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Radial-mounted four-piston brakes replaced the previous six-piston brakes and the front forks were now inverted.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Chassis improvements resulted in higher rigidity and less weight.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] An all digital instrument panel was also introduced and a larger ram-air intake inlet moved to the center over the headlight, running through the headstock.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The bike, designation B1H, carried over to the 2004 model year with just color scheme changes.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The ZX-6RR won the Supersport category award for Masterbike 2004 and placed third overall.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] In 2005, Kawasaki again revamped the ZX-6R.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Engine speed increased again by 1,000 RPM resulting in 131 hp (98 kW) at 12,250 RPM.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The frame and swingarm were updated, but the main changes from its predecessor lay in the design.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The aluminum frame was now painted flat black, fairings were more round, and integrated turn signals were used (euro model).
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The exhaust was now centrally under the seat (a configuration commonly referred to as an undertail exhaust).
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Most of these changes were mirrored in the 599 cc ZX-6RR.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] For the second year in a row, the ZX-6RR again won the Supersport category award for Masterbike 2005 and placed third overall.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The bike carried over to the 2006 model year with minor suspension changes and new color schemes.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] After four years of offering their 636 cc ZX-6R for street use and an entirely separate 599 cc ZX-6RR for displacement-restricted racing classes, Kawasaki offered only one ZX-6R for 2007, and it displaced 599 cc.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Previous years of the ZX-6R's engines were all built from the same basic design, but the all-new engine for 2007 was redesigned from the crankcase up.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] In following with what their competitors had already been doing, Kawasaki's new engine featured a stacked gear arrangement in which the crankshaft, primary drive and countershaft are placed in a triangular format for a shorter, more compact powerplant.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Now about 40 mm smaller in both length and width and it is said to yield greater cornering clearance.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] By using a former 125 cc Grand Prix racer as the ZX-6R's chief development rider, Tomomi Manako, Kawasaki claims a focus has been put on track usage.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Frame, swingarm, suspension, brakes, and body were completely redesigned and the bike shares very few parts from the previous model.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The ZX-6R was carried over to the 2008 model year with just color scheme changes.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] For 2009, Kawasaki dramatically changed the appearance of the ZX-6R to match the more angular look of the ZX-10R.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Kawasaki claims the new ZX-6R is 10 kg lighter than the previous model.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The greatest changes for 2009 were the redesign of the exhaust, now carried low and not requiring the thick under-seat construction of 2008 and especially the introduction of the Showa Big Piston Fork (BPF) suspension for a more progressive brake-dive.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The 2010 ZX-6R is changing once more with an improved engine and slipper clutch.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The exhaust pre-chamber has more space and also limits exhaust noise giving the rider a smoother ride.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] New double bore intake funnels features two available heights which gives performance upgrades in both high and low engine speeds.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] For 2013, Kawasaki reintroduced the ZX-6R 636, while still continuing to sell the regular, 599 cc 2009-2012 ZX-6R at a lower price.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The 2013 ZX-6R 636 is a brand new bike, making it the model with the most power output to date.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Engine displacement has again been increased to 636 cc, with two fuel maps available to choose via a switch on the handlebars.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The new version has increased torque and horsepower, and the increased performance is apparent at lower RPM.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] In Showa's Big Piston Fork - Separate Function Fork (BPF-SFF) suspension, the left leg bar a bigger and stronger spring than the right one, with regulated pre-load.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The right bar has bigger oil damper section, with regulated rebound and compression damping.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] According to the manufacturer, this asymmetric design provides a reduction of the friction inside the fork, significant mass loss and more friendly response of suspension.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The KTRC system uses manipulation of the ignition timing on all 3 traction control modes, while mode 3 (rain mode) also uses a separate throttle controlled by the on-board electronics, to allow faster reaction for wheel over-spin on slippery surfaces.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Traction control and power modes can be adjusted or turned off whenever the throttle is closed, even while riding the bike.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The bike is sold without a steering damper, as customer complaints about the OEM steering damper on previous models prompted Kawasaki to discontinue this feature on subsequent models.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The ZX-6R 636 for 2019 has some updates consisting of: Euro 4 compliance, KQS quickshifter (up only), updated bodywork and seat, LED headlights and updated dashboard.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The claimed horsepower also sees a slight drop from the 2018 model's 96.4 kW (129.3 hp) to 94.9 kW (127.3 hp).
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Through the 2020 model year, Kawasaki sold only the 636 cc (38.8 cu in) displacement Ninja ZX-6R in most markets, while in Japan the 599 cc (36.6 cu in) version continues to be sold alongside the 636 since the model year 2003 onwards.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] In July 2023, Kawasaki announced the 2024 model year for ZX-6R.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The bike meets the Euro 5 emission standards, with yet another slight reduction of horsepower compared to the previous model.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] The ABS has been updated and a redesigned stock exhaust system along with a new front twin headlamp, and for the first time it features a color TFT LCD dashboard.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Andrew Pitt won the Supersport World Championship in 2001 with a ZX-6R, and Kenan Sofuoğlu won it in 2012, 2015 and 2016.
[src:airbox/kawasaki-ninja-zx-6r] Also, Kawasaki won the Supersport World Championship manufacturers title in 2013, 2015 and 2016.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] A **motorcycle** (**motorbike**, **bike**, or, if three-wheeled, a **trike**) is a two or three-wheeled motor vehicle steered by a handlebar from a saddle-style seat.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycle designs vary greatly to suit a range of different purposes: long-distance travel, commuting, cruising, sport (including racing), and off-road riding.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycling is riding a motorcycle and being involved in other related social activities such as joining a motorcycle club and attending motorcycle rallies.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The 1885 Daimler Reitwagen made by Gottlieb Daimler and Wilhelm Maybach in Germany was the first internal combustion petroleum-fueled motorcycle.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In 1894, Hildebrand & Wolfmüller became the first series production motorcycle.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Globally, motorcycles are comparable numerically to cars as a method of transport: in 2021, approximately 58.6 million new motorcycles were sold around the world, while 66.7 million cars were sold over the same period.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In 2022, the top four motorcycle producers by volume and type were Honda, Yamaha, Kawasaki, and Suzuki.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] According to the US Department of Transportation, the number of fatalities per vehicle mile traveled was 37 times higher for motorcycles than for cars.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The term motorcycle has different legal definitions depending on jurisdiction (see § Legal definitions and restrictions).
[src:airbox/motorcycle] There are three major types of motorcycle: street, off-road, and dual purpose.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Within these types, there are many sub-types of motorcycles for different purposes.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] There is often a racing counterpart to each type, such as road racing and street bikes, or motocross including dirt bikes.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Street bikes include cruisers, sportbikes, scooters and mopeds, and many other types.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Off-road motorcycles include many types designed for dirt-oriented racing classes such as motocross and are not street legal in most areas.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Dual purpose machines like the dual-sport style are made to go off-road but include features to make them legal and comfortable on the street as well.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Each configuration offers either specialised advantage or broad capability, and each design creates a different riding posture.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In some countries the use of pillions (rear seats) is restricted.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The first internal combustion, petroleum fueled motorcycle was the Daimler *Reitwagen*.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] It was designed and built by the German inventors Gottlieb Daimler and Wilhelm Maybach in Bad Cannstatt, Germany, in 1885.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] This vehicle was unlike either the safety bicycles or the boneshaker bicycles of the era in that it had zero degrees of steering axis angle and no fork offset, and thus did not use the principles of bicycle and motorcycle dynamics developed nearly 70 years earlier.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Instead, it relied on two outrigger wheels to remain upright while turning.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The inventors called their invention the *Reitwagen* ("riding car").
[src:airbox/motorcycle] It was designed as an expedient testbed for their new engine, rather than a true prototype vehicle.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The first commercial design for a self-propelled cycle was a three-wheel design called the Butler Petrol Cycle, conceived of Edward Butler in England in 1884.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] He exhibited his plans for the vehicle at the Stanley Cycle Show in London in 1884.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The vehicle was built by the Merryweather Fire Engine company in Greenwich, in 1888.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The engine was liquid-cooled, with a radiator over the rear driving wheel.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Speed was controlled by means of a throttle valve lever.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] No braking system was fitted; the vehicle was stopped by raising and lowering the rear driving wheel using a foot-operated lever; the weight of the machine was then borne by two small castor wheels.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The driver was seated between the front wheels.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] It was not, however, a success, as Butler failed to find sufficient financial backing.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Many authorities have excluded steam powered, electric motorcycles or diesel-powered two-wheelers from the definition of a 'motorcycle', and credit the Daimler *Reitwagen* as the world's first motorcycle.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Given the rapid rise in use of electric motorcycles worldwide, defining only internal-combustion powered two-wheelers as 'motorcycles' is increasingly problematic.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The first (petroleum fueled) internal-combustion motorcycles, like the German *Reitwagen*were, however, also the first practical motorcycles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Roper of Roxbury, Massachusetts, who had been demonstrating his machine at fairs and circuses in the eastern U.S. since 1867.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Roper built about 10 steam cars and cycles from the 1860s until his death in 1896.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In 1894, Hildebrand & Wolfmüller became the first series production motorcycle, and the first to be called a motorcycle (German: *Motorrad*).
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Excelsior Motor Company, originally a bicycle manufacturing company based in Coventry, England, began production of their first motorcycle model in 1896.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The first production motorcycle in the US was the Orient-Aster, built by Charles Metz in 1898 at his factory in Waltham, Massachusetts.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In the early period of motorcycle history, many producers of bicycles adapted their designs to accommodate the new internal combustion engine.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] As the engines became more powerful and designs outgrew the bicycle origins, the number of motorcycle producers increased.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Many of the nineteenth-century inventors who worked on early motorcycles often moved on to other inventions.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Daimler and Roper, for example, both went on to develop automobiles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] At the end of the 19th century the first major mass-production firms were set up.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In 1898, Triumph Motorcycles in England began producing motorbikes, and by 1903 it was producing over 500 bikes.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Other British firms were Royal Enfield, Norton, Douglas Motorcycles and Birmingham Small Arms Company who began motorbike production in 1899, 1902, 1907 and 1910, respectively.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Indian began production in 1901 and Harley-Davidson was established two years later.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] By the outbreak of World War I, the largest motorcycle manufacturer in the world was Indian, producing over 20,000 bikes per year.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] During the First World War, motorbike production was greatly ramped up for the war effort to supply effective communications with front line troops.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Messengers on horses were replaced with despatch riders on motorcycles carrying messages, performing reconnaissance and acting as a military police.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] American company Harley-Davidson was devoting over 50% of its factory output toward military contract by the end of the war.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The British company Triumph Motorcycles sold more than 30,000 of its Triumph Type H model to allied forces during the war.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] With the rear wheel driven by a belt, the Model H was fitted with a 499 cc (30.5 cu in) air-cooled four-stroke single-cylinder engine.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] It was also the first Triumph without pedals.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The Model H in particular, is regarded by many as having been the first "modern motorcycle".
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Introduced in 1915 it had a 550 cc side-valve four-stroke engine with a three-speed gearbox and belt transmission.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] It was so popular with its users that it was nicknamed the "Trusty Triumph".
[src:airbox/motorcycle] By 1920, Harley-Davidson was the largest manufacturer, with their motorcycles being sold by dealers in 67 countries.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Amongst many British motorcycle manufacturers, Chater-Lea with its twin-cylinder models followed by its large singles in the 1920s stood out.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Initially, using a converted Woodmann-designed OHV Blackburne engine, it became the first 350 cc to exceed 100 mph (160 km/h), recording 100.81 mph (162.24 km/h) over the flying kilometre during April 1924.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Later, Chater-Lea set a world record for the flying kilometre for 350 cc and 500 cc motorcycles at 102.9 mph (165.6 km/h) for the firm.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Chater-Lea produced variants of these world-beating sports models and became popular among racers at the Isle of Man TT.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] By the late 1920s or early 1930s, DKW in Germany took over as the largest manufacturer.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In the 1950s, streamlining began to play an increasing part in the development of racing motorcycles and the "dustbin fairing" held out the possibility of radical changes to motorcycle design.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] NSU and Moto Guzzi were in the vanguard of this development, both producing very radical designs well ahead of their time.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] NSU produced the most advanced design, but after the deaths of four NSU riders in the 1954–1956 seasons, they abandoned further development and quit Grand Prix motorcycle racing.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Moto Guzzi produced competitive race machines, and until the end of 1957 had a succession of victories.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The following year, 1958, full enclosure fairings were banned from racing by the FIM in the light of the safety concerns.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] From the 1960s through the 1990s, small two-stroke motorcycles were popular worldwide, partly as a result of East German MZs Walter Kaaden's engine work in the 1950s.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In the 21st century, the motorcycle industry is mainly dominated by Indian and Japanese motorcycle companies.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In addition to the large capacity motorcycles, there is a large market in smaller capacity (less than 300 cc) motorcycles, mostly concentrated in Asian and African countries and produced in China and India.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] A Japanese example is the 1958 Honda Super Cub, which went on to become the biggest selling vehicle of all time, with its 60 millionth unit produced in April 2008.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Today, this area is dominated by mostly Indian companies with Hero MotoCorp emerging as the world's largest manufacturer of two wheelers.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Its Splendor model has sold more than 8.5 million to date.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Other major producers are Bajaj and TVS Motors.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycle construction is the engineering, manufacturing, and assembly of components and systems for a motorcycle which results in the performance, cost, and aesthetics desired by the designer.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] With some exceptions, construction of modern mass-produced motorcycles has standardised on a steel or aluminium frame, telescopic forks holding the front wheel, and disc brakes.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Some other body parts, designed for either aesthetic or performance reasons may be added.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] A petrol-powered engine typically consisting of between one and four cylinders (and less commonly, up to eight cylinders) coupled to a manual five- or six-speed sequential transmission drives the swingarm-mounted rear wheel by a chain, driveshaft, or belt.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The repair can be done using a motorcycle lift.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycle fuel economy varies greatly with engine displacement and riding style.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] A streamlined, fully faired Matzu Matsuzawa Honda XL125 achieved 470 mpg‑US (0.50 L/100 km; 560 mpg‑imp) in the Craig Vetter Fuel Economy Challenge "on real highways – in real conditions".
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Due to low engine displacements (100–200 cc (6.1–12.2 cu in)), and high power-to-mass ratios, motorcycles offer good fuel economy.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Under conditions of fuel scarcity like 1950s Britain and modern developing nations, motorcycles claim large shares of the vehicle market.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In the United States, the average motorcycle fuel economy is 44 miles per US gallon (19 km per liter).
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Very high fuel economy equivalents are often derived by electric motorcycles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Electric motorcycles are nearly silent, zero-emission electric motor-driven vehicles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Operating range and top speed are limited by battery technology.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Fuel cells and petroleum-electric hybrids are also under development to extend the range and improve performance of the electric drive system.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] A 2013 survey of 4,424 readers of the US *Consumer Reports* magazine collected reliability data on 4,680 motorcycles purchased new from 2009 to 2012.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The most common problem areas were accessories, brakes, electrical (including starters, charging, ignition), and fuel systems, and the types of motorcycles with the greatest problems were touring, off-road/dual sport, sport-touring, and cruisers.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] There were not enough sport bikes in the survey for a statistically significant conclusion, though the data hinted at reliability as good as cruisers.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] These results may be partially explained by accessories including such equipment as fairings, luggage, and auxiliary lighting, which are frequently added to touring, adventure touring/dual sport and sport touring bikes.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Trouble with fuel systems is often the result of improper winter storage, and brake problems may also be due to poor maintenance.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Of the five brands with enough data to draw conclusions, Honda, Kawasaki and Yamaha were statistically tied, with 11 to 14% of those bikes in the survey experiencing major repairs.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Harley-Davidsons had a rate of 24%, while BMWs did worse, with 30% of those needing major repairs.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] There were not enough Triumph and Suzuki motorcycles surveyed for a statistically sound conclusion, though it appeared Suzukis were as reliable as the other three Japanese brands while Triumphs were comparable to Harley-Davidson and BMW.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Three-fourths of the repairs in the survey cost less than US$200 and two-thirds of the motorcycles were repaired in less than two days.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In spite of their relatively worse reliability in this survey, Harley-Davidson and BMW owners showed the greatest owner satisfaction, and three-fourths of them said they would buy the same bike again, followed by 72% of Honda owners and 60 to 63% of Kawasaki and Yamaha owners.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Two-wheeled motorcycles stay upright while rolling due to a physical property known as conservation of angular momentum in the wheels.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Angular momentum points along the axle, and it "wants" to stay pointing in that direction.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Different types of motorcycles have different dynamics and these play a role in how a motorcycle performs in given conditions.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] For example, one with a longer wheelbase provides the feeling of more stability by responding less to disturbances.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycle tyres have a large influence over handling.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycles must be leaned in order to make turns.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] This lean is induced by the method known as countersteering, in which the rider momentarily steers the handlebars in the direction opposite of the desired turn.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] This practice is counterintuitive and therefore often confusing to novices – and even many experienced motorcyclists.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] With such short wheelbase, motorcycles can generate enough torque at the rear wheel, and enough stopping force at the front wheel, to lift the opposite wheel off the road.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] These actions, if performed on purpose, are known as wheelies and stoppies (or endos) respectively.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Various features and accessories may be attached to a motorcycle either as OEM (factory-fitted) or aftermarket.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Such accessories are selected by the owner to enhance the motorcycle's appearance, safety, performance, or comfort, and may include anything from mobile electronics to sidecars and trailers.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycles have a higher rate of fatal accidents than automobiles or trucks and buses.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] United States Department of Transportation data for 2005 from the Fatality Analysis Reporting System show that for passenger cars, 18.62 fatal crashes occur per 100,000 registered vehicles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] For motorcycles this figure is 75.19 per 100,000 registered vehicles – four times higher than for cars.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The same data shows that 1.56 fatalities occur per 100 million vehicle miles travelled for passenger cars, whereas for motorcycles the figure is 43.47 which is 28 times higher than for cars (37 times more deaths per mile travelled in 2007).
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycle accident rates have increased significantly since the end of the 1990s, while the rates have dropped for passenger cars.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The most common scenario for motorcycle accidents in the United States is a motorist pulling out or turning in front of a motorcyclist, violating their right-of-way.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] This is sometimes called a SMIDSY, an acronym for the motorists' common response of "Sorry mate, I didn't see you".
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcyclists can anticipate and avoid some of these crashes with proper training, increasing their visibility to other traffic, keeping to the speed limits, and not consuming alcohol or other drugs before riding.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The United Kingdom has several organisations dedicated to improving motorcycle safety by providing advanced rider training beyond what is necessary to pass the basic motorcycle licence test.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] These include the Institute of Advanced Motorists (IAM) and the Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents (RoSPA).
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Along with increased personal safety, riders with these advanced qualifications may benefit from reduced insurance costs.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In South Africa, the Think Bike campaign is dedicated to increasing both motorcycle safety and the awareness of motorcycles on the country's roads.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The campaign, while strongest in the Gauteng province, has representation in Western Cape, KwaZulu Natal and the Free State.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] It has dozens of trained marshals available for various events such as cycle races and is deeply involved in numerous other projects such as the annual Motorcycle Toy Run.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycle safety education is offered throughout the United States by organisations including state agencies, non-profit organisations, and corporations.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Most states use the courses designed by the Motorcycle Safety Foundation (MSF), while Oregon and Idaho developed their own.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] All of the training programs include a Basic Rider Course, an Intermediate Rider Course and an Advanced Rider Course.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In Canada, motorcycle rider training is compulsory in Quebec and Manitoba only, but all provinces and territories have graduated licence programs which place restrictions on new drivers until they have gained experience.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Eligibility for a full motorcycle licence or endorsement for completing a Motorcycle Safety course varies by province.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Without the Motorcycle Safety Course the chance of getting insurance for the motorcycle is very low.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The Canada Safety Council, a non-profit safety organisation, offers the Gearing Up program across Canada and is endorsed by the Motorcycle and Moped Industry Council.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Training course graduates may qualify for reduced insurance premiums.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcyclists and motor scooter riders are also exposed to an increased risk of suffering hearing damage such as hearing loss and tinnitus (ringing ears).
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The noise is caused by wind noise while riding, rolling noise from the tyres and the engine itself.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The helmet only provides insufficient protection against high sound pressure levels.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Medicine (as of 2024) is not able to cure hearing damage.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Wearing hearing protection, such as special earplugs for motorcyclists, can help prevent hearing damage.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The motorcyclist's riding position depends on rider body-geometry (anthropometry) combined with the geometry of the motorcycle itself.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] These factors create a set of three basic postures.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Factors of a motorcycle's ergonomic geometry that determine the seating posture include the height, angle and location of footpegs, seat and handlebars.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Factors in a rider's physical geometry that contribute to seating posture include torso, arm, thigh and leg length, and overall rider height.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] While motorcycles are manufactured in standard styles (sport, cruiser, enduro, etc...), certain styles of motorcycle sub-genres have been both independently created, or manufactured in accordance with a pre-existing cultural style.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Styles of note include: Café racers, Choppers, and Streetfighters.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Cultural influence has directly led to the manufacturing of certain styles of motorcycles such as the Café racer.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The stylistic choices and aerodynamic benefits of these custom bikes garnered a tremendous popularity which lead manufacturers to adopt the visual cues, and attempt to mimic the custom builds of these motorcycles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Notably, Harley-Davidson also leaned into a popular custom motorcycle culture (the Chopper), producing the Harley "soft-tail".
[src:airbox/motorcycle] This design attempted to appear as a hard tail chopper style build, while maintaining rear suspension yet having an aggressive riding angle similar to that of the custom builds.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] A motorcycle is broadly defined by law in most countries for the purposes of registration, taxation and rider licensing as a powered two-wheel motor vehicle.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Most countries distinguish between mopeds of 49 cc and the more powerful, larger vehicles, including scooter type motorcycles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Many jurisdictions include some forms of three-wheeled cars as motorcycles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In Nigeria, motorcycles, popularly referred to as *Okada* have been subject of many controversies with regards to safety and security followed by restriction of movement in many states.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In 2020, it was banned in Lagos, Nigeria's most populous city.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In Iran, women are not allowed to ride motorcycles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycles and scooters' low fuel consumption has attracted interest in the United States from environmentalists and those affected by increased fuel prices.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Piaggio Group Americas supported this interest with the launch of a "Vespanomics" website and platform, claiming lower per-mile carbon emissions of 0.4 lb/mile (113 g/km) less than the average car, a 65% reduction, and better fuel economy.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] However, a motorcycle's exhaust emissions may contain 10–20 times more oxides of nitrogen (NOx), carbon monoxide, and unburned hydrocarbons than exhaust from a similar-year passenger car or SUV.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] This is because many motorcycles lack a catalytic converter, and the emission standard is much more permissive for motorcycles than for other vehicles.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] While catalytic converters have been installed in most gasoline-powered cars and trucks since 1975 in the United States, they can present fitment and heat difficulties in motorcycle applications.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] United States Environmental Protection Agency 2007 certification result reports for all vehicles versus on highway motorcycles (which also includes scooters), the average certified emissions level for 12,327 vehicles tested was 0.734.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The average "Nox+Co End-Of-Useful-Life-Emissions" for 3,863 motorcycles tested was 0.8531.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] 54% of the tested 2007-model motorcycles were equipped with a catalytic converter.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] The following table shows maximum acceptable legal emissions of the combination of hydrocarbons, oxides of nitrogen, and carbon monoxide for new motorcycles sold in the United States with 280 cc or greater piston displacement.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] European emission standards for motorcycles are similar to those for cars.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] New motorcycles must meet Euro 5 standards, while cars must meet Euro 6D-temp standards.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Motorcycle emission controls are being updated and it has been proposed to update to Euro 5+ in 2024.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In Asia, motorcycles are a common mode of transportation and are putting significant pressure on the region's environment.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] With a massive number of motorcycles, they contribute significantly to greenhouse gas emissions and urban air pollution.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In India, road transport accounts for about 12% of the country's energy-related CO2 emissions.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In Vietnam, motorcycles contribute up to 87% of the CO emissions and 94% of hydrocarbons (HC) released by vehicles in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] Environmental studies show that motorcycles in Vietnam contribute approximately 29% of NOx, 90% of CO, 65% of NMVOC, and nearly 38% of PM dust in total traffic emissions.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In Thailand, gasoline-powered motorcycles are reported to emit significantly higher pollution per kilometer compared to gasoline-powered cars, exacerbating urban smog.
[src:airbox/motorcycle] In Singapore, the NEA reported that while motorcycles account for only 15 percent of vehicles, they contribute to over 53 percent of carbon monoxide emissions from vehicles.
